00:28:42.320 --> 00:28:47.270
it's very important to make
readers see the humanity of people

00:28:47.270 --> 00:28:51.360
who believe differently
from the way they do.

00:28:51.360 --> 00:28:54.920
And you know, I did
not meet any villains

00:28:54.920 --> 00:28:57.950
when I was doing the five
years of research for this book

00:28:57.950 --> 00:29:02.330
and I didn't write any
villains in the novel.

00:29:02.330 --> 00:29:04.600
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: I want to
touch briefly on research,

00:29:04.600 --> 00:29:08.770
because Julia you both do
research and for that book my lord,

00:29:08.770 --> 00:29:12.060
I can't even begin to
imagine what that was like

00:29:12.060 --> 00:29:16.230
and you wrote an essay
about research.

00:29:16.230 --> 00:29:18.700
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: Oh, the one I
wrote online for Random House?

00:29:18.700 --> 00:29:20.000
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: Yes.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:21.300
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: Oh,
you're a good detective.

00:29:21.300 --> 00:29:23.230
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: Thank you.

00:29:23.230 --> 00:29:26.020
So what are your thoughts
about research,

00:29:26.020 --> 00:29:31.300
when do you let the
research enter into the world

00:29:31.300 --> 00:29:33.500
of the book that you're creating?

00:29:33.500 --> 00:29:38.350
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: For me it depends
on the book that I'm writing.

00:29:38.350 --> 00:29:41.490
You know, if I were writing
the book like Heat and Light,

00:29:41.490 --> 00:29:45.780 position:56%
I think I'd have to undertake some
research early on or midway through.

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:48.260
But my general principle
is that I do research

00:29:48.260 --> 00:29:51.370
as late as I possibly can.

00:29:51.370 --> 00:29:55.870
And there are sort of two
main reasons for that, one,

00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:59.640
is the I'm lazy and I'd rather
just live in my imagination

00:29:59.640 --> 00:30:02.610
and imagine what it would be like.

00:30:02.610 --> 00:30:06.600 position:56%
For instance, I had a character who
was a pastry chef in one of my books

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:10.320
and all sorts of friends
said oh I know a pastry chef,

00:30:10.320 --> 00:30:12.730
you can go spend a day
with a pastry chef.

00:30:12.730 --> 00:30:15.420
Because I really love desert, you
know, I thought that would be great

00:30:15.420 --> 00:30:17.280
because I didn't really
want to do it right away.

00:30:17.280 --> 00:30:19.350
In fact I joked to my friends
the reason that I was writing

00:30:19.350 --> 00:30:23.690
that novel is so that I could
order desert and call it research.

00:30:23.690 --> 00:30:29.190
But I just, I faked
my way through it.

00:30:29.190 --> 00:30:32.070 position:56%
I imagined what I thought everything
was like, the construction

00:30:32.070 --> 00:30:35.040
of a wedding cake and then I
did my research at the very end,

00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:39.080 position:56%
after I had drafted all these
important scenes involving the craft

00:30:39.080 --> 00:30:40.380
of pastry.

00:30:40.380 --> 00:30:43.860
And I was wrong about some
things but here's the thing,

00:30:43.860 --> 00:30:47.210
and this is the second reason
I like to do my research late.

00:30:47.210 --> 00:30:50.110
You know, I was that kid who loved
being in the library doing my --

00:30:50.110 --> 00:30:52.850
and I wrote the class paper
that was five times as long

00:30:52.850 --> 00:30:56.380
as everybody else's whether it
was on volcanos or you know,

00:30:56.380 --> 00:30:57.690
I was actually obsessed
with volcanos.

00:30:57.690 --> 00:31:00.440
I did one on volcanos and one
on Pompeii and Herculaneum.

00:31:00.440 --> 00:31:05.060
So I just love finding
stuff out and the problem is

00:31:05.060 --> 00:31:07.620
when you find really cool
stuff out you want to share it.

00:31:07.620 --> 00:31:11.040
And you want to wedge it in there,
you want it to be in the novel

00:31:11.040 --> 00:31:15.140 position:56%
and maybe it doesn't belong there so
if you've already got the framework,

00:31:15.140 --> 00:31:19.380 position:56%
it's harder to squeeze in all these
really cool stories about the origin

00:31:19.380 --> 00:31:24.000
of wedding cakes in
Hungary and Czechoslovakia

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:26.070
and the cool stuff I
found out by reading

00:31:26.070 --> 00:31:28.160
about the history of wedding cakes.

00:31:28.160 --> 00:31:32.850
And also their architectural
integrity and I'm sure

00:31:32.850 --> 00:31:37.420
that if I were researching I'm
sure you found out a lot of stuff

00:31:37.420 --> 00:31:40.360
that didn't have a
place in the book.

00:31:40.360 --> 00:31:43.640
So how did you approach
it for this book?

00:31:43.640 --> 00:31:45.960
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Haigh: Well, this
book I had to do some research

00:31:45.960 --> 00:31:49.300
on the front end just to know
what I was talking about.

00:31:49.300 --> 00:31:51.480
My favorite way of doing
research is interviews

00:31:51.480 --> 00:31:55.850
and I interview obsessively, I
talk to lots and lots of people

00:31:55.850 --> 00:31:58.570
and this has been true for
every novel I've written.

00:31:58.570 --> 00:32:03.950
And it's -- yes it is research
but it's more than that.

00:32:03.950 --> 00:32:07.560
I'm not looking for particular
information so much as I want

00:32:07.560 --> 00:32:12.550
to hear the voices of people living
these different kinds of lives.

00:32:12.550 --> 00:32:15.090
And I find that doing
a lot of interviews

00:32:15.090 --> 00:32:18.030
on the front end suggests
possibilities for characters

00:32:18.030 --> 00:32:20.270
that suggest possibilities
for story.

00:32:20.270 --> 00:32:26.350
Not just you know, factual things
I need to know but once I start

00:32:26.350 --> 00:32:27.870
to do research I see possibilities

00:32:27.870 --> 00:32:29.800
in the story I wouldn't
have seen otherwise.

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:32.170
So for me it is integral
to the writing of it,

00:32:32.170 --> 00:32:34.330
it's part of how I find the story.

00:32:34.330 --> 00:32:37.460
And it's more true for some
novels than for others.

00:32:37.460 --> 00:32:41.830
Heat and Light was a
massive research undertaking,

00:32:41.830 --> 00:32:45.190
more so than I realized when
I started out writing it.

00:32:45.190 --> 00:32:49.600 position:56%
But you know, it was in the process
of doing research that I found a lot

00:32:49.600 --> 00:32:52.900
of the story and I often
don't know what I'm looking

00:32:52.900 --> 00:32:54.200
for when I set out looking.

00:32:54.200 --> 00:32:58.940
You know, I just want somebody
to say something interesting.

00:32:58.940 --> 00:33:02.640
And if I hear something that
fascinates me I'll follow it,

00:33:02.640 --> 00:33:08.260
I give myself permission always to
follow the thread that fascinates.

00:33:08.260 --> 00:33:12.050
Because I have to believe that if
I find something fascinating enough

00:33:12.050 --> 00:33:15.230
that there's something in there the
reader will be fascinated by too.

00:33:15.230 --> 00:33:20.350 position:56%
So it's really you know, I'm casting
a very wide net in the beginning

00:33:20.350 --> 00:33:23.040
when I do research, I don't
quite know what I'm looking for.

00:33:23.040 --> 00:33:25.330
I'm hoping to find my
book out there somewhere.

00:33:25.330 --> 00:33:27.980
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: Do you work
closely with your editor?

00:33:27.980 --> 00:33:32.480
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Haigh: Not on
the front end, no I don't.

00:33:32.480 --> 00:33:34.980
I have a terrific editor
and I value him

00:33:34.980 --> 00:33:37.720
and he's immensely
helpful with later drafts.

00:33:37.720 --> 00:33:41.710
Nobody, nobody ever sees
my first draft of anything.

00:33:41.710 --> 00:33:44.470
Nobody should ever have to.

00:33:44.470 --> 00:33:47.970
My first drafts are hideous
and really I just want

00:33:47.970 --> 00:33:51.550
to burn them always so I
don't share them with anyone.

00:33:51.550 --> 00:33:54.690
I have a couple of readers
who will see maybe a second

00:33:54.690 --> 00:33:58.520
or maybe a third draft,
never the first draft.

00:33:58.520 --> 00:34:04.850
And my editor really sees a
fourth or a fifth draft maybe.

00:34:04.850 --> 00:34:07.450
Part of the problem is I don't want
to know what anybody else thinks

00:34:07.450 --> 00:34:09.400
until I know what I think.

00:34:09.400 --> 00:34:12.860
You know, it really muddies
the water if you get opinions

00:34:12.860 --> 00:34:15.240
from people before you've
solidified your own.

00:34:15.240 --> 00:34:19.000
So I'm very, very cautious
about asking for feedback

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:22.010
and also cautious about
using up my good readers

00:34:22.010 --> 00:34:26.280
because guess what you only get
somebody's first impression once.

00:34:26.280 --> 00:34:28.480
If someone is a good friend
you know, he might be willing

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:31.680
to read it a second or third time
but he's never going to be able

00:34:31.680 --> 00:34:33.620
to read it with those fresh eyes.

00:34:33.620 --> 00:34:37.270
So I don't want to use up that
precious first reading from one

00:34:37.270 --> 00:34:40.400
of my good readers until I'm
sure I've gotten it as far

00:34:40.400 --> 00:34:42.220
as I can get it on my own.

00:34:42.220 --> 00:34:44.060
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: Julia do you work
closely with your editor?

00:34:44.060 --> 00:34:48.180
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Haigh: Well,
I -- ditto what she said.

00:34:48.180 --> 00:34:55.900
I love my editor and my weakness
is that every book that I turn

00:34:55.900 --> 00:35:00.690
in to my editor when that draft
is really done has pretentions

00:35:00.690 --> 00:35:01.990
of war and peace.

00:35:01.990 --> 00:35:07.490
I turn in these massive things and
now they're done electronically

00:35:07.490 --> 00:35:09.810
but I've been writing long enough
to have actually had to mail

00:35:09.810 --> 00:35:13.390
