00:37:55.380 --> 00:37:59.750 position:56%
So he doesn't get to see it any
sooner than anybody else does either

00:37:59.750 --> 00:38:01.540
and some of my friends
think that's strange.

00:38:01.540 --> 00:38:05.460
But no he does not get to see
it until my editor and my agent

00:38:05.460 --> 00:38:09.020
and my husband all see
it at the same time.

00:38:09.020 --> 00:38:10.650
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: Jennifer you once said

00:38:10.650 --> 00:38:15.510
that each book is an engineering
feat, that it has to work

00:38:15.510 --> 00:38:18.850
and I was really intrigued by
that and I'd like you to say more.

00:38:18.850 --> 00:38:22.080 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Haigh: Yeah,
absolutely, you know, I'm fascinated

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:25.640
by machines, I love writing about
machines and I think of a novel

00:38:25.640 --> 00:38:28.820 position:56%
as an extremely complicated machine.

00:38:28.820 --> 00:38:33.340
The best comparison I can think
of, some of you are old enough

00:38:33.340 --> 00:38:36.340
to remember this old board
game called Mouse Trap.

00:38:36.340 --> 00:38:37.640
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: Oh, I love that.

00:38:37.640 --> 00:38:39.730
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Haigh: Who remembers
Mouse Trap, oh, like everyone.

00:38:39.730 --> 00:38:43.720
Okay, so Mouse Trap for those
who don't know it the object

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:45.940
of the game is to build
this complicated,

00:38:45.940 --> 00:38:49.010
ridiculous Rube Goldberg
type mouse trap

00:38:49.010 --> 00:38:52.180
out of the dispirit plastic parts.

00:38:52.180 --> 00:38:55.780
So there is like a rain gutter
and there's a stair case

00:38:55.780 --> 00:38:58.530
and there's a crank you
turn and there's a bathtub

00:38:58.530 --> 00:39:01.720
and these unlikely parts
that you string them together

00:39:01.720 --> 00:39:04.720
and finally it's a trap
that will catch a mouse

00:39:04.720 --> 00:39:07.080 position:56%
in the most convoluted possible way.

00:39:07.080 --> 00:39:11.080
That to me is the perfect
metaphor for writing a novel,

00:39:11.080 --> 00:39:17.450
that you are building a story out
of found objects in a certain way

00:39:17.450 --> 00:39:20.800
and it's a mechanism
that you want to be able

00:39:20.800 --> 00:39:24.050
to flip a switch and have it work.

00:39:24.050 --> 00:39:28.170
So when the first draft what I'm
doing is building this mousetrap

00:39:28.170 --> 00:39:29.880
out of these dispirit parts.

00:39:29.880 --> 00:39:33.440
Then what I'm doing afterward
is just testing and retesting

00:39:33.440 --> 00:39:37.360
and retesting the trap until
it actually catches the mouse.

00:39:37.360 --> 00:39:40.680
So I write a first draft, and I
kind of reverse engineer the thing

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:43.160
and I look at where are
the pinch points, you know,

00:39:43.160 --> 00:39:46.870
where does the ball roll off track,
where do the gears get gummed

00:39:46.870 --> 00:39:49.010
and I go in and fix those
in a very mechanistic way.

00:39:49.010 --> 00:39:51.990
And then I run the trap again
and I find the ball gets stuck

00:39:51.990 --> 00:39:56.180
in a different palce then I
go an diagnose those problems.

00:39:56.180 --> 00:39:57.830
So it's a very -- my process

00:39:57.830 --> 00:40:01.260
of revision is quite mechanical
and I really enjoy that.

00:40:01.260 --> 00:40:05.390
You know, I think of a novel as
being like a car, I love cars

00:40:05.390 --> 00:40:08.190
and I find cars beautiful.

00:40:08.190 --> 00:40:11.040
But you know, when you turn the
key in the ignition all you care is

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:12.900
that the engine turns over.

00:40:12.900 --> 00:40:18.490
So with a novel yeah you want
to build a beautiful machine

00:40:18.490 --> 00:40:21.670
but the thing in the
end just needs to work.

00:40:21.670 --> 00:40:24.630
So that's kind of what my
revision process looks like.

00:40:24.630 --> 00:40:26.760
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: Does that
make sense to you?

00:40:26.760 --> 00:40:31.720
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: I'm listening
really hard, I'm terrible with cars

00:40:31.720 --> 00:40:35.450
so maybe I need to
pay more attention.

00:40:35.450 --> 00:40:40.010
That's a fascinating metaphor and
you know, with my students you talk

00:40:40.010 --> 00:40:44.420
about the engine turning over and
obviously I teach fiction writing

00:40:44.420 --> 00:40:47.620
and the first thing that
I have my students do

00:40:47.620 --> 00:40:52.610
for the first class is they have
to bring in the first page only

00:40:52.610 --> 00:40:55.690
of a favorite short story or novel.

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:58.540
That they love in its entirety but
they really love the beginning too.

00:40:58.540 --> 00:41:03.280
And we dissect that beginning
because I say if you don't start

00:41:03.280 --> 00:41:07.540
in the right place, if you
don't pull the reader in

00:41:07.540 --> 00:41:08.840
and I don't mean you
have to hook them

00:41:08.840 --> 00:41:10.900
with a dead body or
anything like that.

00:41:10.900 --> 00:41:12.490
I mean it may be language
that hooks them in,

00:41:12.490 --> 00:41:14.600
it may be a lingering
question that's already there

00:41:14.600 --> 00:41:16.580
on that first page.

00:41:16.580 --> 00:41:20.690
Then you're already the
journey is off to a bad start.

00:41:20.690 --> 00:41:24.230
So I focus a lot on that, you know,
is it beginning in the right place,

00:41:24.230 --> 00:41:26.920
is it beginning in the right
tone and we dissect beginnings.

00:41:26.920 --> 00:41:28.700
So I think that's kind of
like the engine turning over.

00:41:28.700 --> 00:41:34.550
And then you know, after that
it's a lot more work of course.

00:41:34.550 --> 00:41:38.740
I love what Sue Miller
said about writing a novel,

00:41:38.740 --> 00:41:40.670
she said that writing a novel is

00:41:40.670 --> 00:41:46.300
like knitting an argyle sock
the size of a football field.

00:41:48.020 --> 00:41:50.820
Maybe that's more monotonous.

00:41:50.820 --> 00:41:53.350
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: And a word
about endings,

00:41:53.350 --> 00:41:55.550 position:56%
