00:42:01.040 --> 00:42:06.300
on what you think is the
palce you want to end.

00:42:06.300 --> 00:42:08.310
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Haigh: I
find endings so difficult

00:42:08.310 --> 00:42:10.930
that it makes me hate the
whole first draft of the book

00:42:10.930 --> 00:42:13.810
because I'm living in fear that
I'm going to get the ending wrong.

00:42:13.810 --> 00:42:16.260
You know, we've all had
this experience as readers

00:42:16.260 --> 00:42:18.100
where you fall in love
with the book.

00:42:18.100 --> 00:42:21.200
You fall in love with the
characters and the ending is

00:42:21.200 --> 00:42:22.710
so horribly disappointing
that you want

00:42:22.710 --> 00:42:24.780
to through the thing
across the room.

00:42:24.780 --> 00:42:28.830 position:56%
Now you will forever remember that
as a novel with the terrible ending.

00:42:28.830 --> 00:42:31.760
You won't remember it as the
novel with the great beginning.

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:36.590
So it's kind of like you know, when
you're learning to fly a plane,

00:42:36.590 --> 00:42:38.780
it's great if you have a
beautiful take off but if screw

00:42:38.780 --> 00:42:41.080
up the landing no one is
going to remember that.

00:42:41.080 --> 00:42:42.380
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: Including you.

00:42:42.380 --> 00:42:45.140 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Haigh: Very much like
that writing a novel, so I have lots

00:42:45.140 --> 00:42:50.570
of anxiety around it and you know,
I usually do get the ending wrong

00:42:50.570 --> 00:42:51.970
on the first draft, I don't know

00:42:51.970 --> 00:42:55.600
that I've ever really gotten
it right on the first go.

00:42:55.600 --> 00:43:01.050
So it is fraught and it is the
sort of thing that you keep writing

00:43:01.050 --> 00:43:03.750
and writing and writing
until you find it.

00:43:03.750 --> 00:43:06.830
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: Well, the way
I write is I don't write draft,

00:43:06.830 --> 00:43:11.060
after draft, after draft I write
forward back, forward back.

00:43:11.060 --> 00:43:13.520
I think partly because
I'm so obsessive

00:43:13.520 --> 00:43:15.270
about getting sentences right.

00:43:15.270 --> 00:43:19.430
Things that I can't -- I'll
remember a sentence two pages ago

00:43:19.430 --> 00:43:20.860
that just wasn't right.

00:43:20.860 --> 00:43:24.630
So every time I sit down to write I
may intend to write ten more pages

00:43:24.630 --> 00:43:26.810
but I may end up spending
three hours working

00:43:26.810 --> 00:43:28.580
on the last ten pages that I wrote.

00:43:28.580 --> 00:43:31.930
I don't make myself go forward
if I'm not going to get there.

00:43:31.930 --> 00:43:36.680
So what happens is it really takes
me a long time to reach the end

00:43:36.680 --> 00:43:39.910
and during that time I may
have had different ideas

00:43:39.910 --> 00:43:42.550
about the ending I'm
going to arrive at.

00:43:42.550 --> 00:43:48.320
But by the time I get to that last
chapter literally I've been working

00:43:48.320 --> 00:43:51.860
on the book for probably at
least a year if not more.

00:43:51.860 --> 00:43:56.310
And so I'm almost more
qualified to find the right end,

00:43:56.310 --> 00:44:01.860
that doesn't mean it won't change
but I'm not doing first draft,

00:44:01.860 --> 00:44:04.690
second draft, third
draft and so forth.

00:44:04.690 --> 00:44:08.090
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: And that leads exactly
to the question I wanted to ask

00:44:08.090 --> 00:44:11.730
which is your both
midcareer novelist

00:44:11.730 --> 00:44:15.610
with five or six novels each.

00:44:15.610 --> 00:44:20.130
When you think back to
when you started writing

00:44:20.130 --> 00:44:24.400
and the things you thought you'd be
exploring or that made you curious

00:44:24.400 --> 00:44:30.160
or that drove you to the page, in
the first place do you see changes

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:34.360
from the writer you are now?

00:44:34.360 --> 00:44:39.910
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: Well, you know
talked about you would not return

00:44:39.910 --> 00:44:43.750
to your town, to Pennsylvania.

00:44:43.750 --> 00:44:46.210
And I was certain that
I would never return

00:44:46.210 --> 00:44:48.010
to the characters in my first book.

00:44:48.010 --> 00:44:51.660
Well, in fact some of them have
recurred in two further books.

00:44:51.660 --> 00:44:53.800 position:56%
So I never say never about anything.

00:44:53.800 --> 00:44:57.940
I think that one thing
I've learned to do

00:44:57.940 --> 00:45:00.700
through my books is I've
learned to be more forgiving

00:45:00.700 --> 00:45:02.530
of myself, for one thing.

00:45:02.530 --> 00:45:04.950
Not to be so scared
that I can't do it

00:45:04.950 --> 00:45:07.000
because I've done it before, right.

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:11.870
So if I get stuck I don't get
as panicky, I also I did not go

00:45:11.870 --> 00:45:14.510
to a MFA program or have any
creative writing training,

00:45:14.510 --> 00:45:18.470 position:56%
I actually majored in art in college
and I took only two English classes.

00:45:18.470 --> 00:45:21.820
I didn't really like them, I mean
I was always good at writing.

00:45:21.820 --> 00:45:25.450
But I really started writing
fiction seriously in my early 30's

00:45:25.450 --> 00:45:30.940
and so all I had to go on were
essays I'd read about writing.

00:45:30.940 --> 00:45:36.190
You know I bought writing guides
and I find that I absorbed

00:45:36.190 --> 00:45:38.670
so many dogmatic pieces of advice

00:45:38.670 --> 00:45:42.110
from writers whether they were
Stephen King or Anne Lamott.

00:45:42.110 --> 00:45:44.890
That they didn't fit me
and I felt guilty or I felt

00:45:44.890 --> 00:45:46.910
like I'm not a real writer
because I don't write every day.

00:45:46.910 --> 00:45:50.500
Or I'm not a real writer
because I don't do this or that.

00:45:50.500 --> 00:45:54.580
And I've learned that every
writer makes his or her own rules.

00:45:54.580 --> 00:45:57.070
It doesn't mean you can't read
what other people have to say.

00:45:57.070 --> 00:46:01.790
So I feel much more confident and
maybe able to take more chances.

00:46:01.790 --> 00:46:06.270
But I also find that certain themes
come back again and again for me.

00:46:06.270 --> 00:46:09.520
And I'm not one of those
writers who is going

00:46:09.520 --> 00:46:12.560
to write the completely different
novel every time I sit down.

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:13.860
I think there are people like that.

00:46:13.860 --> 00:46:16.720
I think Jennifer Egan is
one who really has a --

00:46:16.720 --> 00:46:19.700
but you know the world of
paining and I returned to that.

00:46:19.700 --> 00:46:23.420
I'm more like the painter
Morandi who I really revered

00:46:23.420 --> 00:46:27.300
who did these amazing still
life's at variations on a theme

00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:29.410
and I think that's
who I am as a writer.

00:46:29.410 --> 00:46:32.700
So if I return, if characters
come back to me, if I write again

00:46:32.700 --> 00:46:35.340
about New York in the plague
years which is something I seem

00:46:35.340 --> 00:46:36.930
to return to again and again.

00:46:36.930 --> 00:46:43.340
Then that's who I am and I
occupy that territory more

00:46:43.340 --> 00:46:47.890 position:56%
and more confidently I think and not
feeling like I need to make excuses

00:46:47.890 --> 00:46:49.310
if I write about the same thing.

00:46:49.310 --> 00:46:51.430 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: You still have questions
about it that you want to explore.

00:46:51.430 --> 00:46:52.760
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: I do, yeah.

00:46:52.760 --> 00:46:54.060
&gt;&gt; Jo Reed: Jennifer?

00:46:54.060 --> 00:46:55.360
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Haigh: You know

00:46:55.360 --> 00:46:57.760
when I was writing my first novel
I had no idea what I was doing.

00:46:57.760 --> 00:47:01.550 position:56%
It's writing the first novel is kind
of like running the first marathon.

00:47:01.550 --> 00:47:04.150
You're not trying to
win you just don't want

00:47:04.150 --> 00:47:06.730
to die while you're doing it.

00:47:06.730 --> 00:47:10.640
So my goal was just to live through
the writing of that first novel

00:47:10.640 --> 00:47:13.800
and to write a book
that I'd want to read.

00:47:13.800 --> 00:47:17.500
You know, I don't have particularly
exotic tastes as a reader

00:47:17.500 --> 00:47:19.360
and I figure if it's
a book that I want

00:47:19.360 --> 00:47:22.490 position:56%
to read then somebody somewhere else
is going to want to read it also.

00:47:22.490 --> 00:47:26.420
So that's all I was trying to do
is live through the writing process

00:47:26.420 --> 00:47:29.980
and write a book that
I would want to read.

00:47:29.980 --> 00:47:33.260
As I've gotten further
along you know,

00:47:33.260 --> 00:47:38.670
I'm drawn to some different
subjects I guess.

00:47:38.670 --> 00:47:43.050
But that's still really the guiding
principle to me to write a book

00:47:43.050 --> 00:47:44.350
that I would want to read.

00:47:44.350 --> 00:47:47.800
When I wrote my first novel
I thought okay it's going

00:47:47.800 --> 00:47:49.140
to be easier now.

00:47:49.140 --> 00:47:51.220
You know, now I know
how to write a novel,

00:47:51.220 --> 00:47:53.230
it will never be this hard again.

00:47:53.230 --> 00:47:55.810
I was entirely wrong about that.

00:47:55.810 --> 00:47:58.030
What I learned was yes I
know how to write a novel

00:47:58.030 --> 00:47:59.820
but I only know how
to write that novel.

00:47:59.820 --> 00:48:03.140
And the lessons I learned were
not particularly portable,

00:48:03.140 --> 00:48:06.940
I could not apply them to my
second or my third or my forth.

00:48:06.940 --> 00:48:11.390 position:56%
So in a certain way it's starting
at zero every time for me, you know,

00:48:11.390 --> 00:48:14.230
I always feel like I'm an imposter,

00:48:14.230 --> 00:48:16.000
I am completely unqualified
to do this.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:19.220
&gt;&gt; Julia Glass: Well, I think we
all -- what we do is so weird,

00:48:19.220 --> 00:48:22.840
